title.narrative: EQUITABLE AND INCLUSIVE EDUCATION

description.narrative: By 2023 school leaders and teachers have enhanced capacity to deliver equitable, inclusive, relevant and quality education in safe learning environments., which contributes to Access To Quality Learning Opportunities, Access To Quality Learning Opportunities (Covid), Climate Change, Disaster Risks And Envionmental Degradation, Cross Sectoral - Children With Disabilities, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Promotion Of Care, Mental Health And Psychosocial Well-Being And Justice, Protection From Violence, Exploitation, Abuse And Neglect. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, girls and boys, particularly the rural and urban poor, have increased access to inclusive, equitable, relevant and quality early childhood and basic education that promotes lifelong learning, including in emergencies.

title.narrative: By 2023 school leaders and teachers have enhanced capacity to deliver equitable, inclusive, relevant and quality education in safelearning environments.

description.narrative: Despite COVID19-related challenges and constraints, progress was made in increasing quality education opportunities particularly among disadvantaged populations through strengthening of community preschools, multilingual education, inclusive education and life skills education programmes. New distance teaching and learning approaches were expanded at pre-primary, primary and secondary levels including interventions for special needs of children with disabilities and children from ethnic minority communities. To support continued quality learning during school closure, UNICEF led the development and distribution of a Home-Learning Package, reaching 760,000 Grade 1 and 2 students and their teachers, including guidance to parents on how to support children’s learning at home. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:04/01/2022
